Kutsinta

Makes ~16 pieces | Serves ~4

Ingredients

Batter
	•	1 cup (120 g) rice flour
	•	2/3 cup (80 g) tapioca starch
	•	0.9 cup (180 g) dark brown sugar
	•	2 cups (480 ml) water
	•	2 teaspoons food-grade lye water (kansui)

Finishing
	•	1 cup (80 g) fresh grated coconut
	•	2 teaspoons coconut oil (for greasing molds)

⸻

Method
	1.	Prep Steamer & Molds
Bring steamer water to a full boil.
Wrap the lid with a clean towel to prevent condensation.
Lightly grease molds with coconut oil.
	2.	Dissolve Sugar
Stir brown sugar into water until completely dissolved.
Warm gently if needed; liquid must be clear with no granules.
	3.	Mix Batter
Whisk rice flour and tapioca starch into the sugar solution until fully smooth and lump-free.
Rest 5 minutes to hydrate starches.
	4.	Add Lye Water
Stir in lye water evenly.
Batter should turn light amber and remain fluid and glossy.
	5.	Fill Molds
Pour batter into molds, filling about 90%.
Tap gently to release trapped air bubbles.
	6.	Steam
Steam over a steady, rolling boil for 35–40 minutes, covered.
Do not open the lid.
Kutsinta should be fully set, translucent, and glossy.
	7.	Finish
Rest 5 minutes.
Unmold while warm and top with grated coconut.

⸻

Optional Enhancements
	•	Use muscovado sugar for deeper molasses bitterness
	•	Steam with a pandan leaf for aroma (remove before serving)
	•	Lightly salt the coconut topping for contrast
	•	If no lye water: use baked baking soda solution (color and chew slightly reduced)